# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tarantool
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] Tarantool is an in-memory computing platform consisting of a database and an application server.
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] It is distributed under BSD 2-Clause terms.
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] Tarantool is ideal for data-enriched components of scalable Web architecture: queue servers, caches, stateful Web applications.
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] To download and install Tarantool as a binary package for your OS or using Docker, please see the download instructions.
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] To build Tarantool from source, see detailed instructions in the Tarantool documentation.
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] To find modules, connectors and tools for Tarantool, check out our Awesome Tarantool list.
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] Please report bugs to our issue tracker.
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] We also warmly welcome your feedback on the discussions page and questions on Stack Overflow.
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] We accept contributions via pull requests.
[src:tarantool/blob-readme-md] Thank you for your interest in Tarantool!
[src:tarantool/developers] Set the logic of data processing using the programming languages Lua (inside Tarantool) and Rust and C (for additional modules).
[src:tarantool/developers] In Tarantool, the code and the database are in the same address space.
[src:tarantool/developers] Processing data at the place where it is stored allows you to reduce delays in the execution of operations.
[src:tarantool/developers] Tarantool allows you to select synchronous or asynchronous replication mode depending on the task and the nature of the data.
[src:tarantool/developers] Asynchronous replication guarantees maximum cluster speed and minimal delays.
[src:tarantool/developers] And synchronous replication, linearizable reads and the MVCC (multi-version concurrency control) engine together provide the highest possible level of consistency — strict serializable.
[src:tarantool/developers] You can create indexes for any data in Tarantool.
[src:tarantool/developers] Searching indexed fields is faster and more predictable.
[src:tarantool/developers] If you need to select similar data based on several criteria, you can create multiple indexes for a single table.
[src:tarantool/developers] Tarantool supports both regular and JSON indexes.
[src:tarantool/developers] In Tarantool, you can choose a data storage model.
[src:tarantool/developers] Use a tabular format, and when the number and names of fields are not known in advance — JSON.
[src:tarantool/developers] For a table, you can set a format that fixes the data types in the columns: for the entire table or only for a part of it.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:tarantool/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua originated in 1993 as a language for extending software applications to meet the increasing demand for customization at the time.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] It provided the basic facilities of most procedural programming languages, but more complicated or domain-specific features were not included; rather, it included mechanisms for extending the language, allowing programmers to implement such features.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] As Lua was intended to be a general embeddable extension language, the designers of Lua focused on improving its speed, portability, extensibility and ease-of-use in development.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua was created in 1993 by Roberto Ierusalimschy, Luiz Henrique de Figueiredo, and Waldemar Celes, members of the Computer Graphics Technology Group (Tecgraf) at the Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro, in Brazil.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] From 1977 until 1992, Brazil had a policy of strong trade barriers (called a market reserve) for computer hardware and software, believing that Brazil could and should produce its own hardware and software.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] In that climate, Tecgraf's clients could not afford, either politically or financially, to buy customized software from abroad; under the market reserve, clients would have to go through a complex bureaucratic process to prove their needs couldn't be met by Brazilian companies.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Those reasons led Tecgraf to implement the basic tools it needed from scratch.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua's predecessors were the data-description and configuration languages Simple Object Language (SOL) and Data-Entry Language (DEL).
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] They had been independently developed at Tecgraf in 1992–1993 to add some flexibility into two different projects (both were interactive graphical programs for engineering applications at Petrobras company).
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] There was a lack of any flow-control structures in SOL and DEL, and Petrobras felt a growing need to add full programming power to them.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua 1.0 was designed in such a way that its object constructors, being then slightly different from the current light and flexible style, incorporated the data-description syntax of SOL (hence the name Lua: *Sol* meaning "Sun" in Portuguese, and *Lua* meaning "Moon").
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Dobb's Journal*, Lua's creators also state that LISP and Scheme with their single, ubiquitous data-structure mechanism (the list) were a major influence on their decision to develop the table as the primary data structure of Lua.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua semantics have been increasingly influenced by Scheme over time, especially with the introduction of anonymous functions and full lexical scoping.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Several features were added in new Lua versions.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Versions of Lua prior to version 5.0 were released under a license similar to the BSD license.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] From version 5.0 onwards, Lua has been licensed under the MIT License.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Both are permissive free software licences and are almost identical.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua is commonly described as a "multi-paradigm" language, providing a small set of general features that can be extended to fit different problem types.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua does not contain explicit support for inheritance, but allows it to be implemented with metatables.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] In general, Lua strives to provide simple, flexible meta-features that can be extended as needed, rather than supply a feature-set specific to one programming paradigm.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] As a result, the base language is light; the full reference interpreter is only about 293 kB compiled and easily adaptable to a broad range of applications.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] As a dynamically typed language intended for use as an extension language or scripting language, Lua is compact enough to fit on a variety of host platforms.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] It supports only a small number of atomic data structures such as Boolean values, numbers (double-precision floating point and 64-bit integers by default) and strings.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Typical data structures such as arrays, sets, lists and records can be represented using Lua's single native data structure, the table, which is essentially a heterogeneous associative array.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua implements a small set of advanced features such as first-class functions, garbage collection, closures, proper tail calls, coercion (automatic conversion between string and number values at run time), coroutines (cooperative multitasking) and dynamic module loading.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The declaration of a variable, without a value.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] A comment in Lua starts with a double-hyphen and runs to the end of the line, similar to Ada, Eiffel, Haskell, SQL and VHDL.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Multi-line strings and comments are marked with double square brackets.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua has one type of conditional test: `if then end` with optional `else` and `elseif then` execution control constructs.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua has four types of conditional loops: the `while` loop, the `repeat` loop (similar to a `do while` loop), the numeric `for` loop and the generic `for` loop.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Loops can also be nested (put inside of another loop).
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Any future calls to `print` will now be routed through the new function, and because of Lua's lexical scoping, the old print function will only be accessible by the new, modified print.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] A new closure for the variable `x` is created every time `addto` is called, so that each new anonymous function returned will always access its own `x` parameter.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The closure is managed by Lua's garbage collector, just like any other object.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Tables are the most important data structures (and, by design, the only built-in composite data type) in Lua and are the foundation of all user-created types.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] They are associative arrays with addition of automatic numeric key and special syntax.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] A table is a set of key and data pairs, where the data is referenced by key; in other words, it is a hashed heterogeneous associative array.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Tables are created using the `{}` constructor syntax.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Tables are always passed by reference (see Call by sharing).
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] A key (index) can be any value except `nil` and NaN, including functions.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] A table is often used as structure (or record) by using strings as keys.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Because such use is very common, Lua features a special syntax for accessing such fields.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] By using a table to store related functions, it can act as a namespace.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Tables are automatically assigned a numerical key, enabling them to be used as an array data type.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The first automatic index is 1 rather than 0 as it is for many other programming languages (though an explicit index of 0 is allowed).
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] A numeric key `1` is distinct from a string key `"1"`.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The length of a table `t` is defined to be any integer index `n` such that `t[n]` is not `nil` and `t[n+1]` is `nil`; moreover, if `t[1]` is `nil`, `n` can be zero.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] For a regular array, with non-nil values from 1 to a given `n`, its length is exactly that `n`, the index of its last value.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] If the array has "holes" (that is, nil values between other non-nil values), then `#t` can be any of the indices that directly precedes a `nil` value (that is, it may consider any such nil value as the end of the array).
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Using a hash map to emulate an array is normally slower than using an actual array; however, Lua tables are optimized for use as arrays to help avoid this issue.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Extensible semantics is a key feature of Lua, and the metatable allows powerful customization of tables.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The following example demonstrates an "infinite" table.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] For any `n`, `fibs[n]` will give the `n`-th Fibonacci number using dynamic programming and memoization.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Although Lua does not have a built-in concept of classes, object-oriented programming can be emulated using functions and tables.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] An object is formed by putting methods and fields in a table.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Inheritance (both single and multiple) can be implemented with metatables, delegating nonexistent methods and fields to a parent object.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] There is no such concept as "class" with these techniques; rather, prototypes are used, similar to Self or JavaScript.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] New objects are created either with a factory method (that constructs new objects from scratch) or by cloning an existing object.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Here, `setmetatable` tells Lua to look for an element in the `Vector` table if it is not present in the `vec` table.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] `vec.magnitude`, which is equivalent to `vec["magnitude"]`, first looks in the `vec` table for the `magnitude` element.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The `vec` table does not have a `magnitude` element, but its metatable delegates to the `Vector` table for the `magnitude` element when it's not found in the `vec` table.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua provides some syntactic sugar to facilitate object orientation.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] To declare member functions inside a prototype table, one can use `function table:func(args)`, which is equivalent to `function table.func(self, args)`.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Calling class methods also makes use of the colon: `object:func(args)` is equivalent to `object.func(object, args)`.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] It is possible to use metatables to mimic the behavior of class inheritance in Lua.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] In this example, we allow vectors to have their values multiplied by a constant in a derived class.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] It is also possible to implement multiple inheritance; `__index` can either be a function or a table.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Operator overloading can also be done; Lua metatables can have elements such as `__add`, `__sub` and so on.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua programs are not interpreted directly from the textual Lua file, but are compiled into bytecode, which is then run on the Lua virtual machine (VM).
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The compiling process is typically invisible to the user and is performed during run-time, especially when a just-in-time compilation (JIT) compiler is used, but it can be done offline to increase loading performance or reduce the memory footprint of the host environment by leaving out the compiler.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua bytecode can also be produced and executed from within Lua, using the `dump` function from the string library and the `load/loadstring/loadfile` functions.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua version 5.5.0 is implemented in approximately 32,000 lines of C code.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Like most CPUs, and unlike most virtual machines (which are stack-based), the Lua VM is register-based, and therefore more closely resembles most hardware design.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The register architecture both avoids excessive copying of values, and reduces the total number of instructions per function.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The virtual machine of Lua 5 is one of the first register-based pure VMs to have a wide use.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Parrot and Android's Dalvik are two other well-known register-based VMs.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua is intended to be embedded into other applications, and provides a C API for this purpose.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The API is divided into two parts: the Lua core and the Lua auxiliary library.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The Lua API's design eliminates the need for manual reference counting (management) in C code, unlike Python's API.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The API, like the language, is minimalist.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Advanced functions are provided by the auxiliary library, which consists largely of preprocessor macros which assist with complex table operations.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua provides functions to push and pop most simple C data types (integers, floats, etc.) to and from the stack, and functions to manipulate tables through the stack.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The Lua stack is somewhat different from a traditional stack; the stack can be indexed directly, for example.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Negative indices indicate offsets from the top of the stack.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] For example, −1 is the top (most recently pushed value), while positive indices indicate offsets from the bottom (oldest value).
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Marshalling data between C and Lua functions is also done using the stack.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] To call a Lua function, arguments are pushed onto the stack, and then the `lua_call` is used to call the actual function.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] When writing a C function to be directly called from Lua, the arguments are read from the stack.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] The C API also provides some special tables, located at various "pseudo-indices" in the Lua stack.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] At `LUA_GLOBALSINDEX` prior to Lua 5.2 is the globals table, `_G` from within Lua, which is the main namespace.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] There is also a registry located at `LUA_REGISTRYINDEX` where C programs can store Lua values for later retrieval.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Besides standard library (core) modules it is possible to write extensions using the Lua API.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Extension modules are shared objects which can be used to extend the functions of the interpreter by providing native facilities to Lua scripts.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Lua scripts may load extension modules using `require`, just like modules written in Lua itself, or with `package.loadlib`.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] When a C library is loaded via `require('foo')` Lua will look for the function `luaopen_foo` and call it, which acts as any C function callable from Lua and generally returns a table filled with methods.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] A growing set of modules termed *rocks* are available through a package management system named LuaRocks, in the spirit of CPAN, RubyGems and Python eggs.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Prewritten Lua bindings exist for most popular programming languages, including other scripting languages.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] For C++, there are a number of template-based approaches and some automatic binding generators.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] In video game development, Lua is widely used as a scripting language, mainly due to its perceived ease of embedding, fast execution, and short learning curve.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Notable games which use Lua include *Roblox*, *Garry's Mod*, *World of Warcraft*, *Payday 2*, *Project Zomboid*, *Phantasy Star Online 2*, *Dota 2*, *Crysis*, and many others.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] Also, Lua is used in non-video game software, such as Adobe Lightroom, Moho, iClone, Aerospike, and some system software in FreeBSD and NetBSD, and used as a template scripting language on MediaWiki using the Scribunto extension.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] In 2003, a poll conducted by GameDev.net showed that Lua was the most popular scripting language for game programming.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] On 12 January 2012, Lua was announced as a winner of the Front Line Award 2011 from the magazine *Game Developer* in the category Programming Tools.
[src:tarantool/lua-programming-language] In addition, the Lua users community provides some *power patches* on top of the reference C implementation.
[src:tarantool/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:tarantool/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:tarantool/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:tarantool/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:tarantool/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:tarantool/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:tarantool/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:tarantool/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:tarantool/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:tarantool/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:tarantool/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:tarantool/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:tarantool/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:tarantool/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:tarantool/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:tarantool/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:tarantool/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:tarantool/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:tarantool/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:tarantool/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:tarantool/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:tarantool/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:tarantool/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:tarantool/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:tarantool/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:tarantool/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:tarantool/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:tarantool/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:tarantool/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:tarantool/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:tarantool/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:tarantool/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:tarantool/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Tarantool maintains data in memory and ensures crash resistance with write-ahead logging and snapshotting.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] It includes a Lua interpreter and interactive console, but also accepts connections from programs in several other languages.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Mail.Ru, one of the largest Internet companies in Russia, started the project in 2008 as part of the development of Moy Mir (My World) social network.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] In 2010 for a project head it hired a former technical lead from MySQL.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Open-source contributors have been active especially in the area of external-language connectors for C, Golang, Perl, PHP, Python, Ruby, and node.js.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Tarantool became part of the Mail.Ru backbone, used for dynamic content such as user sessions, unsent instant messages, task queues, and a caching layer for traditional relational databases such as MySQL or PostgreSQL.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] By 2014 Tarantool had also been adopted by the social network services Badoo and Odnoklassniki (the latter is affiliated with Mail.Ru since 2010).
[src:tarantool/tarantool] All data is maintained in memory (RAM), with data persistence ensured by write-ahead logging and snapshotting, and for those reasons some industry observers have compared Tarantool to Membase.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Replication is asynchronous and failover (getting one Tarantool server to take over from another) is possible either from a replica server or from a "hot standby" server.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Tarantool uses Lua-style coroutines and asynchronous I/O.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] The result is that application programs or stored procedures must be written with cooperative multitasking in mind, rather than the more popular preemptive multitasking.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] For database storage the basic unit is a **tuple**.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Tuples in tuple sets handle the same role as rows in tables for relational databases.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Tuples have an arbitrary number of fields, and fields do not need names.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Every tuple in a database has one (unique not null) primary key and one or more secondary keys, which are enabled for immediate lookup via indexes.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Supported index types are B-tree, hash, bitmap, and R-tree (spatial).
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Fields in a tuple are type-agnostic or can have specific numeric or string data types.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Users may insert, update, delete, or select if they have been granted appropriate privileges.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] In 2017 Tarantool introduced an optional on-disk storage engine which allows databases larger than memory size.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] In 2019 Tarantool introduced an optional SQL interface which complies with most of the mandatory features of the official SQL standard.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Tarantool comes as part of the official distributions for some Linux distros such as Debian, Fedora or Ubuntu.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] The Tarantool organization also supplies downloads for other Linux distributions, OS X, and FreeBSD.
[src:tarantool/tarantool] Tarantool can be extended with modules installed using LuaRocks, and it includes its own selection of extension rocks.
